Rectal cancer in the setting of ulcerative  colitis s/p neoadjuvant therapy

[end section id="20102"]

[start section id="20103"]

Mr. Knopp is a 65-year-old male who has a history of chronic ulcerative colitis. A colonoscopy on 22 September 2009 revealed  a circumferential lesion starting at approximately 5-cm to approximately 10-cm.  Colonoscopy also showed a couple polyps in the sigmoid colon which were not biopsied and some pseudopolyps throughout the colon as well.  Biopsies of the rectal lesion shows invasive, moderately differentiated grade 3 of 4 adenocarcinoma. A CT-scan on September 22, 2009 showed poorly-defined rectal mass. Mild bilateral inguinal and external iliac lymphadenopathy with the largest left external iliac lymph node measuring 1.3-cm. He has completed his preoperative neoadjuvant therapy and comes now for surgical management of his rectal cancer.

[end section id="20103"]

